\title{Writing hookify rules}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{version}{0.1.0}

\meta{description}{This skill should be used when the user asks to "create a hookify rule", "write a hook rule", "configure hookify", "add a hookify rule", or needs guidance on hookify rule syntax and patterns.}

\subtree{
\title{Writing Hookify Rules}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Hookify rules are markdown files with YAML frontmatter that define patterns to watch for and messages to show when those patterns match. Rules are stored in \code{\startverb .claude/hookify.{rule-name}.local.md\stopverb} files.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rule File Format}
\subtree{
\title{Basic Structure}
\pre{\startverb
---
name: rule-identifier
enabled: true
event: bash|file|stop|prompt|all
pattern: regex-pattern-here
---

Message to show Claude when this rule triggers.
Can include markdown formatting, warnings, suggestions, etc.
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Frontmatter Fields}
\p{\strong{name} (required): Unique identifier for the rule}

\ul{
\li{Use kebab-case: \code{\startverb warn-dangerous-rm\stopverb}, \code{\startverb block-console-log\stopverb}}
\li{Be descriptive and action-oriented}
\li{Start with verb: warn, prevent, block, require, check}
}

\p{\strong{enabled} (required): Boolean to activate/deactivate}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb true\stopverb}: Rule is active}
\li{\code{\startverb false\stopverb}: Rule is disabled (won't trigger)}
\li{Can toggle without deleting rule}
}

\p{\strong{event} (required): Which hook event to trigger on}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb bash\stopverb}: Bash tool commands}
\li{\code{\startverb file\stopverb}: Edit, Write, MultiEdit tools}
\li{\code{\startverb stop\stopverb}: When agent wants to stop}
\li{\code{\startverb prompt\stopverb}: When user submits a prompt}
\li{\code{\startverb all\stopverb}: All events}
}

\p{\strong{action} (optional): What to do when rule matches}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb warn\stopverb}: Show message but allow operation (default)}
\li{\code{\startverb block\stopverb}: Prevent operation (PreToolUse) or stop session (Stop events)}
\li{If omitted, defaults to \code{\startverb warn\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{pattern} (simple format): Regex pattern to match}

\ul{
\li{Used for simple single-condition rules}
\li{Matches against command (bash) or new_text (file)}
\li{Python regex syntax}
}

\p{\strong{Example:}}

\pre{\startverb
event: bash
pattern: rm\s+-rf
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advanced Format (Multiple Conditions)}
\p{For complex rules with multiple conditions:}

\pre{\startverb
---
name: warn-env-file-edits
enabled: true
event: file
conditions:
  - field: file_path
    operator: regex_match
    pattern: \.env$
  - field: new_text
    operator: contains
    pattern: API_KEY
---

You're adding an API key to a .env file. Ensure this file is in .gitignore!
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Condition fields:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb field\stopverb}: Which field to check}
\li{For bash: \code{\startverb command\stopverb}}
\li{For file: \code{\startverb file_path\stopverb}, \code{\startverb new_text\stopverb}, \code{\startverb old_text\stopverb}, \code{\startverb content\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb operator\stopverb}: How to match}
\li{\code{\startverb regex_match\stopverb}: Regex pattern matching}
\li{\code{\startverb contains\stopverb}: Substring check}
\li{\code{\startverb equals\stopverb}: Exact match}
\li{\code{\startverb not_contains\stopverb}: Substring must NOT be present}
\li{\code{\startverb starts_with\stopverb}: Prefix check}
\li{\code{\startverb ends_with\stopverb}: Suffix check}
\li{\code{\startverb pattern\stopverb}: Pattern or string to match}
}

\p{\strong{All conditions must match for rule to trigger.}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Message Body}
\p{The markdown content after frontmatter is shown to Claude when the rule triggers.}

\p{\strong{Good messages:}}

\ul{
\li{Explain what was detected}
\li{Explain why it's problematic}
\li{Suggest alternatives or best practices}
\li{Use formatting for clarity (bold, lists, etc.)}
}

\p{\strong{Example:}}

\pre{\startverb
⚠️ **Console.log detected!**

You're adding console.log to production code.

**Why this matters:**
- Debug logs shouldn't ship to production
- Console.log can expose sensitive data
- Impacts browser performance

**Alternatives:**
- Use a proper logging library
- Remove before committing
- Use conditional debug builds
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Event Type Guide}
\subtree{
\title{bash Events}
\p{Match Bash command patterns:}

\pre{\startverb
---
event: bash
pattern: sudo\s+|rm\s+-rf|chmod\s+777
---

Dangerous command detected!
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Common patterns:}}

\ul{
\li{\startverb Dangerous commands: `rm\s+-rf`, `dd\s+if=`, `mkfs`\stopverb}
\li{\startverb Privilege escalation: `sudo\s+`, `su\s+`\stopverb}
\li{\startverb Permission issues: `chmod\s+777`, `chown\s+root`\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{file Events}
\p{Match Edit/Write/MultiEdit operations:}

\pre{\startverb
---
event: file
pattern: console\.log\(|eval\(|innerHTML\s*=
---

Potentially problematic code pattern detected!
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Match on different fields:}}

\pre{\startverb
---
event: file
conditions:
  - field: file_path
    operator: regex_match
    pattern: \.tsx?$
  - field: new_text
    operator: regex_match
    pattern: console\.log\(
---

Console.log in TypeScript file!
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Common patterns:}}

\ul{
\li{\startverb Debug code: `console\.log\(`, `debugger`, `print\(`\stopverb}
\li{\startverb Security risks: `eval\(`, `innerHTML\s*=`, `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`\stopverb}
\li{\startverb Sensitive files: `\.env$`, `credentials`, `\.pem$`\stopverb}
\li{Generated files: \code{\startverb node_modules/\stopverb}, \code{\startverb dist/\stopverb}, \code{\startverb build/\stopverb}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{stop Events}
\p{Match when agent wants to stop (completion checks):}

\pre{\startverb
---
event: stop
pattern: .*
---

Before stopping, verify:
- [ ] Tests were run
- [ ] Build succeeded
- [ ] Documentation updated
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Use for:}}

\ul{
\li{Reminders about required steps}
\li{Completion checklists}
\li{Process enforcement}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{prompt Events}
\p{Match user prompt content (advanced):}

\pre{\startverb
---
event: prompt
conditions:
  - field: user_prompt
    operator: contains
    pattern: deploy to production
---

Production deployment checklist:
- [ ] Tests passing?
- [ ] Reviewed by team?
- [ ] Monitoring ready?
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Pattern Writing Tips}
\subtree{
\title{Regex Basics}
\p{\strong{Literal characters:} Most characters match themselves}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb rm\stopverb} matches "rm"}
\li{\code{\startverb console.log\stopverb} matches "console.log"}
}

\p{\strong{Special characters need escaping:}}

\ul{
\li{\startverb `.` (any char) → `\.` (literal dot)\stopverb}
\li{\startverb `(` `)` → `\(` `\)` (literal parens)\stopverb}
\li{\startverb `[` `]` → `\[` `\]` (literal brackets)\stopverb}
}

\p{\strong{Common metacharacters:}}

\ul{
\li{\startverb `\s` - whitespace (space, tab, newline)\stopverb}
\li{\startverb `\d` - digit (0-9)\stopverb}
\li{\startverb `\w` - word character (a-z, A-Z, 0-9, _)\stopverb}
\li{\code{\startverb .\stopverb} - any character}
\li{\code{\startverb +\stopverb} - one or more}
\li{\code{\startverb *\stopverb} - zero or more}
\li{\code{\startverb ?\stopverb} - zero or one}
\li{\code{\startverb |\stopverb} - OR}
}

\p{\strong{Examples:}}

\pre{\startverb
rm\s+-rf         Matches: rm -rf, rm  -rf
console\.log\(   Matches: console.log(
(eval|exec)\(    Matches: eval( or exec(
chmod\s+777      Matches: chmod 777, chmod  777
API_KEY\s*=      Matches: API_KEY=, API_KEY =
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Testing Patterns}
\p{Test regex patterns before using:}

\pre{\startverb
python3 -c "import re; print(re.search(r'your_pattern', 'test text'))"
\stopverb}

\p{Or use online regex testers (regex101.com with Python flavor).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Pitfalls}
\p{\strong{Too broad:}}

\pre{\startverb
pattern: log    # Matches "log", "login", "dialog", "catalog"
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
Better: `console\.log\(|logger\.`
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Too specific:}}

\pre{\startverb
pattern: rm -rf /tmp  # Only matches exact path
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
Better: `rm\s+-rf`
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Escaping issues:}}

\ul{
\li{\startverb YAML quoted strings: `"pattern"` requires double backslashes `\\s`\stopverb}
\li{\startverb YAML unquoted: `pattern: \s` works as-is\stopverb}
\li{\strong{Recommendation}: Use unquoted patterns in YAML}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{File Organization}
\p{\strong{Location:} All rules in \code{\startverb .claude/\stopverb} directory \strong{Naming:} \code{\startverb .claude/hookify.{descriptive-name}.local.md\stopverb} \strong{Gitignore:} Add \code{\startverb .claude/*.local.md\stopverb} to \code{\startverb .gitignore\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{Good names:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb hookify.dangerous-rm.local.md\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb hookify.console-log.local.md\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb hookify.require-tests.local.md\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb hookify.sensitive-files.local.md\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{Bad names:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb hookify.rule1.local.md\stopverb} (not descriptive)}
\li{\code{\startverb hookify.md\stopverb} (missing .local)}
\li{\code{\startverb danger.local.md\stopverb} (missing hookify prefix)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Creating a Rule}
\ol{
\li{Identify unwanted behavior}
\li{Determine which tool is involved (Bash, Edit, etc.)}
\li{Choose event type (bash, file, stop, etc.)}
\li{Write regex pattern}
\li{Create \code{\startverb .claude/hookify.{name}.local.md\stopverb} file in project root}
\li{Test immediately - rules are read dynamically on next tool use}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Refining a Rule}
\ol{
\li{Edit the \code{\startverb .local.md\stopverb} file}
\li{Adjust pattern or message}
\li{Test immediately - changes take effect on next tool use}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Disabling a Rule}
\p{\strong{Temporary:} Set \code{\startverb enabled: false\stopverb} in frontmatter \strong{Permanent:} Delete the \code{\startverb .local.md\stopverb} file}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Examples}
\pre{\startverb
See `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/examples/` for complete examples:
\stopverb}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb dangerous-rm.local.md\stopverb} - Block dangerous rm commands}
\li{\code{\startverb console-log-warning.local.md\stopverb} - Warn about console.log}
\li{\code{\startverb sensitive-files-warning.local.md\stopverb} - Warn about editing .env files}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Reference}
\p{\strong{Minimum viable rule:}}

\pre{\startverb
---
name: my-rule
enabled: true
event: bash
pattern: dangerous_command
---

Warning message here
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Rule with conditions:}}

\pre{\startverb
---
name: my-rule
enabled: true
event: file
conditions:
  - field: file_path
    operator: regex_match
    pattern: \.ts$
  - field: new_text
    operator: contains
    pattern: any
---

Warning message
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Event types:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb bash\stopverb} - Bash commands}
\li{\code{\startverb file\stopverb} - File edits}
\li{\code{\startverb stop\stopverb} - Completion checks}
\li{\code{\startverb prompt\stopverb} - User input}
\li{\code{\startverb all\stopverb} - All events}
}

\p{\strong{Field options:}}

\ul{
\li{Bash: \code{\startverb command\stopverb}}
\li{File: \code{\startverb file_path\stopverb}, \code{\startverb new_text\stopverb}, \code{\startverb old_text\stopverb}, \code{\startverb content\stopverb}}
\li{Prompt: \code{\startverb user_prompt\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{Operators:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb regex_match\stopverb}, \code{\startverb contains\stopverb}, \code{\startverb equals\stopverb}, \code{\startverb not_contains\stopverb}, \code{\startverb starts_with\stopverb}, \code{\startverb ends_with\stopverb}}
}
}
}